Foot & mouth disease - Argentina (06) 20010513.0924
Date: 18 May 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Agencia EFE, 16 May 2001 [edited

New Source of Foot-and-mouth Disease Found in Argentina
--------------------------------------------------
On Wednesday, Argentine health authorities confirmed reports of a new
source of foot-and-mouth disease (FMD) in livestock south of the Colorado
River, an indication the disease has crossed the health barrier that was
established when it was first detected in the country.
The outbreak was detected some 50 kilometers (30 miles) south of the river,
near the city of Villarino in Buenos Aires province, according to the
National Animal Health and Quality Service (SENASA). This area had been
considered free of FMD. Up until Tuesday, 567 cases of the disease had been
reported in the country, according to the SENASA.
Argentine daily Rio Negro reported [that a ranch owner in the area warned
that 2 cows from a group of 80 appeared to have been infected with the
disease. Laboratory tests carried out last Monday in Buenos Aires confirmed
the 2 cattle were infected with FMD.
Following official regulations, all livestock within a 3-kilometer
(2-mile) radius of the source of infection were quarantined, while the
area within a 15-kilometer (9-mile) radius was declared under strict
surveillance.
Having denied the existence of the disease for several months, Argentine
authorities finally acknowledged the appearance of FMD in mid-March [2001,
which immediately prompted Brazil, the United States and Britain, among
other important markets, to ban Argentine beef imports.
Argentine beef exports fell more than 60 percent in the first quarter
this year, while beef producers are losing some $50 million monthly due
to the absence of these foreign markets, the CICC, Argentina's beef
chamber of commerce, reported.
According to provisional reports for this year's first quarter, Argentina
exported 37 455 tons of cattle at a value of $66.4 million, which
represents a 64.1 percent drop in volume and a 61.3 percent decrease in
value compared to the same period last year.
Argentina is the fourth-largest beef exporter worldwide, and, in May
2000, the South American country was declared free of foot-and-mouth
disease by the International Organization for Epizootics (OIE).
Argentina's status has been suspended and may be stripped during the
organization's assembly in Paris, to be held in the next few days.
