[2
Date: 18 May 2001
From: Matias Sacla <msacla@yahoo.com>
Source: Reuters, 16 May 2001 [edited
<http://news.excite.com/news/r/010516/16/food-argentina-disease>

Argentina finds foot-and-mouth in Patagonia
-------------------------------------------
Health authorities found cattle infected with the foot-and-mouth disease
(FMD) virus in the historically disease-free zone of Patagonia in southern
Argentina, the national
food and animal health inspection agency Senasa said. "There are 2
outbreaks," said a Senasa spokeswoman.
Senasa said the infected animals were found in Rio Negro province, an
area in which the transport of cattle and meat products with bones is
banned.
The agency set up the sanitary barrier to protect cattle in Rio Negro and
other Patagonian provinces as part of an extensive plan to contain the
disease.
Last week, Senasa said authorities incinerated more than 2 tons of meat
with bone being illegally transported to the Patagonian province of Chubut,
south of Rio Negro.
This week's discovery of infected animals marks the failure of efforts to
prevent the spread of the virus, which is easily transported on clothing,
vehicles and even in the air.
Argentina, South America's second-biggest beef producer, lost nearly all
its export markets in March when officials said they had discovered
infected animals. That put in danger some $600 million in annual meat
exports.
The U.S. Department of Agriculture's (USDA) attache in Buenos Aires last
week cut his estimate for Argentine beef exports this year to 220 000
tonnes, or about 44 percent lower than the export forecast at the
beginning of the year.
